    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-10-20T15:57:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-10-20T15:57:00-05:00" n="388"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                <head>388. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Laos</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d388fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 751J.00/10–156. Secret; Priority. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BPM1">Byrne</persName> and <persName>Pierre</persName>
                        <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss>. Sales of <gloss target="#t_ICA1"
                            >ICA</gloss>; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_SWJ1">Sebald</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_JHP1">Jones</persName>, and <persName>Robert G.
                            Barnes</persName>, Special Assistant to the Secretary for Mutual
                        Security Affairs; approved by <persName>Robertson</persName>; and cleared in
                        draft with <gloss target="#t_ICA1">ICA</gloss> and Defense. Repeated to
                        London, Paris, Ottawa, New Delhi, Saigon, Phnom Penh, and <gloss
                            target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-10-20T16:57:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 20, 1956—4:57 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>448. Joint State–Defense–<gloss target="#t_ICA1">ICA</gloss> message. Vientiane
                    515 repeated London 85 Paris 108 Ottawa 75 Saigon 104 Bangkok Phnom Penh New
                    Delhi Unnumbered.<note n="2" xml:id="d388fn2">
                        <ref target="#d386">Document 386</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Concur suggested initial U.S. position on integration <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> troops, including <gloss target="#t_PEO1"
                            >PEO</gloss>/ARMA point restricting <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> in
                        command positions. Believe latter point should be made in initial
                        presentation, though we recognize we may have yield later if <gloss
                            target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> unable accept.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We not clear whether you intend take initiative presenting proposal to
                            <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> or wish hold in readiness as
                        rebuttal <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> plan when latter fully
                        formulated. From here appears advisable wait see what <gloss
                            target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> produce, provided you consulted before
                            <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> presents its plan to <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>With respect numbered paragraph 2 reference telegram, we should be
                        interested know what mechanism <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> would use
                        fund costs maintaining <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> effectives during
                        screening period.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>In discussions with <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> request you make
                        point <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 120<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d388fn3">
                            <ref target="#d367">Document 367</ref>.</note> that U.S. will consider
                            <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> troop integration in light over-all
                        political settlement achieved by <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss>. (We
                        would not wish make binding commitment on reintegration plan only later find
                            <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> making undesirable concessions other
                        scores which would impair controls on integrated troops.)</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Any U.S. funding <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> reindoctrination and
                        training described reference telegram should come from amounts available
                        military budget support, i.e., $35.6 million <gloss target="#t_CY1"
                            >CY</gloss> 1956 and $20 million <gloss target="#t_CY1">CY</gloss> 1957,
                        or alternatively from possible savings or deferment low priority projects
                            <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1957 economic program.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Advise estimated local currency cost <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>
                        integration.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>We share your view paramount importance properly executed <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> integration for survival Laos, but believe
                            <gloss target="#t_RLG1">RLG</gloss> can operate program within foregoing
                        financial limits.<note n="4" xml:id="d388fn4">In telegram 680 from
                            Vientiane, October 31, the Embassy reported that it intended to hold its
                            plan on integration of the Pathet Lao in readiness, that it did not know
                            how the Royal Government would fund the Pathet Lao effectives during the
                            screening period, but it was sure that the United States would be the
                            ultimate payer. The Embassy was unable to accurately estimate the costs
                            of integration of the Pathet Lao effectives into the National Army.
                            (Department of State, Central Files, 751J.00/10–3155)</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
